The Nines hotel sold to Pebblebrook Hotel Trust for $127 million













5
Gallery: The Nines hotel





Print
Email


Elliot Njus | The Oregonian/OregonLive

	



	



By

	
		
	
		
			
	
		
	
	
	
	
	Elliot Njus | The Oregonian/OregonLive

The Oregonian
 Email the author | Follow on Twitter
on July 17, 2014 at  3:32 PM, updated July 17, 2014 at  5:57 PM









 comments




















A Maryland hotel trust paid $127 million for The Nines hotel in downtown Portland, it announced Thursday, several months after the Portland Development Commission took a buyout on the loans it made toward the hotel's development.
Pebblebrook Hotel Trust said it had acquired the 331-room hotel from Sage Hospitality, which will stay on as operator. It will continue to operate on the Starwood's Luxury Collection brand.
The acquisition is no surprise; the trust earlier applied for a liquor license to take over the hotel's restaurants.
The trust said it would put $6 to $8 million into a refresh of the hotel that will begin this year.
And an acquisition was said to be in the offing in March when the PDC accepted an offer to buy out its $18.2 million in loans for $11.5 million — writing down $6.7 million of the loans' face value, but getting a premium over selling the debt on the open market, according to an appraisal. 
The Nines opened in 2008 after a $133 million renovation of the former Meier & Frank Building backed in part by the PDC. The PDC board voted to make the loans cash-flow dependent in the economic downturn, and the hotel never started making regular payments.
While considering the buyout, PDC officials said the agency was unlikely to realize the full face value of the loans, based on an a December 2012 appraisal that valued the hotel at $100 million. The hotel owed $98.3 in debt senior to the PDC loans.
With the $127 million price tag announced Thursday, it appears the PDC might have been in a position to recover more of the loan's face value than it recognized.
"It's easy to judge now knowing all this additional information," PDC spokesman Shawn Uhlman said Thursday. "We didn't have all this information in March. I think it absolutely was the right decision ... to get the funds we were able to get."
Sage, the equity partner in the project, also didn't receive the full amount it put into the project, Uhlman said, though it retains the management contract for the hotel.
Uhlman added the $11.5 million from the deal would be sent to the PDC shortly now that the transaction is final. The money will be reinvested in the River District urban renewal area.
That the purchase price had risen dramatically from the earlier appraisal speaks to improvements in the Portland hotel market, said Tracy Marks, the general manager of the downtown Hilton Portland & Executive Tower.
"Demand continues to improve in the market and rates are improving, and values of assets are improving because of that," Marks said.
The Nines' sale price comes out to nearly $384,000 a room. Some other recent downtown hotel sales:

The 782-room Hilton sold in November 2012 for $101.5 million, or about $130,000 a room.
Pebblebrook bought the 174-room Hotel Modera in 2013 for $47.5 million, or $273,000 a room.
In May, the 256-room Courtyard Marriott Portland City Center was sold for $64.9 million, or $254,000 a room.

A number of hotels have are also proposed or recently completed in the downtown area, including the recently opened Residence Inn by Marriott in the Pearl District, a proposed RiverPlace Hyatt House hotel and a proposed (as yet unnamed) downtown luxury Hilton hotel.
On the east side, the Red Lion Hotel near the Oregon Convention Center will close in September and reopen next year as a luxury boutique hotel.
And the Metro regional government has agreed to subsidize a $212 million 600-room Hyatt Regency through $60 million in revenue bonds, along with $18 million in state and local loans and grants.
-- Elliot Njus


































